WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.310 --> 00:00:15.610
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Shadl:
Good afternoon,

00:00:15.610 --> 00:00:18.770
thank you for being here today.

00:00:18.770 --> 00:00:23.750
Welcome to the Library
of Congress.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:25.590
My name is Susanne
Shadl, I am the chief

00:00:25.590 --> 00:00:27.940
of the Hispanic Division.

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:29.810
I have the privilege of
working with a tremendous team

00:00:29.810 --> 00:00:33.820
of librarians, including several
in the audience, thank you all

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:37.940
for your work, to improve access
to diverse publications written

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:39.700
in Spanish, Portuguese, English

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:43.340
and several indigenous
languages of the Americas.

00:00:43.340 --> 00:00:46.100
Today we are fortunate
to partner internally

00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:49.090
with the Poetry and Literature
Center, and externally

00:00:49.090 --> 00:00:51.230
with the Uruguayan Embassy.

00:00:51.230 --> 00:00:53.930
If you're here for
"Another voice sings,

00:00:53.930 --> 00:00:56.270
celebrating Uruguayan
women poets" you're

00:00:56.270 --> 00:00:57.570
in the right place.

00:00:57.570 --> 00:01:02.280
If you came for something else,
we hope you'll stay [laughter].

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:04.560
For me and my division
it is an honor

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:07.490
to welcome a tremendous
panel comprised of writers,

00:01:07.490 --> 00:01:10.850
translators, teachers,
professors, for a reading

00:01:10.850 --> 00:01:13.110
that celebrates the
strong tradition

00:01:13.110 --> 00:01:15.300
of Uruguayan women poets,

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.980
and recent publications
reflecting four generations

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:21.120
of Uruguayan poetry,
written by women.

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:25.500
That's an important
thing for me today.

00:01:25.500 --> 00:01:27.690
In addition to hearing
the work of Silvia Guerra,

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:32.830
who's here with us today,
you will also hear work

00:01:32.830 --> 00:01:37.260
from Amanda Berenger,
Marosa Di Giorgio,

00:01:37.260 --> 00:01:38.560
Circe Maia and Melissa Machado.

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:45.040
I have to plug my division in
the work they do to some extent

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:49.010
at these events, so if you're
not familiar with the handbook

00:01:49.010 --> 00:01:52.220
of Latin American studies,
and you searched the handbook

00:01:52.220 --> 00:01:55.450
or Latin American studies on
our catalogue which is online

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:58.840
and anybody has access
to it, you will find all

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:01.770
of these authors and
connections to other authors

00:02:01.770 --> 00:02:08.230
and to other work, so I would
invite you to check that out

00:02:08.230 --> 00:02:09.750
and see where those
lengths take you.

00:02:09.750 --> 00:02:15.410
And if you prefer the
book format, volume 66,

00:02:15.410 --> 00:02:23.440
actually has a very
important entry on our guest

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:26.190
of honor today, Silvia Guerra.

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:27.490
Okay. One plug, there's
more coming, I'm sorry.

00:02:27.490 --> 00:02:29.730
This event is inspired by part
by a previous event called

00:02:29.730 --> 00:02:32.340
"Celebrating Idea
Vilariño's poetry".

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:36.200
An audio file of that event can
also be found in our catalogue

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:38.640
by searching "Idea Vilariño".

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:41.720
I'm going to spell that
because I there it spelled that,

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:45.660
then the web address where
you're going to find it, okay?

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:48.350
So, the name in quotation
marks will take you

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:49.940
where you need to go.

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:57.540
Idea, I-D-E-A, Vilariño,
V-I-L-A-R-I-Ñ --

00:02:57.540 --> 00:03:00.920
that's the N with the
little stinging on top,

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:02.220
in case there's anybody here

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:05.550
that isn't Spanish
speaking, O, okay.

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:09.370
Today we welcome Uruguayan
poet as I said, Silvia Guerra.

00:03:09.370 --> 00:03:12.630
You have this information
in your --

00:03:12.630 --> 00:03:16.040
hopefully you all have
a program, but I'm going

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:17.880
to go ahead for the
purpose of the audio

00:03:17.880 --> 00:03:20.970
and tell you a little bit
about each of our speakers.

00:03:20.970 --> 00:03:26.050
Her books include "Un mar
enmadrugado", "Pulso",

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:28.040
"Estampas de un tapiz".

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:31.400
She's also the author of
"Todo comienza lugar",

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:37.230
coedited with Cuban poet José
Kozer, and "Fuera de regato".

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:41.450
From 2009 to 2011
she was coeditor

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:46.080
of the seminal Uruguayan poetry
press "La flauta mágica".

00:03:46.080 --> 00:03:49.480
In 2012 she received
the Morosoli Prize

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:52.510
in poetry for her career.

00:03:52.510 --> 00:03:57.510
Yesterday Catalina Gomez, who
works in the Hispanic division,

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:01.890
taped Silva Guerra for our
archive of Hispanic literature

00:04:01.890 --> 00:04:05.560
on tape, and eventually that
recording will be available

00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:09.300
to all of you, but in the
meantime I hope you check

00:04:09.300 --> 00:04:13.140
out that archive and see
what other Uruguayan poets

00:04:13.140 --> 00:04:15.860
and writers and other
Latin American poets

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:18.500
and writers are there and you
can get there by going to www --

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:22.050
I'm going to give you
the website this time,

00:04:22.050 --> 00:04:29.580
loc.gov/RR/Hispanic/archive,
okay?

00:04:29.580 --> 00:04:32.800
Also, today we have several
other esteemed guests,

00:04:32.800 --> 00:04:36.700
Jesse Lee Kercheval is
a translator and author

00:04:36.700 --> 00:04:40.880
of 14 books of poetry,
fiction, non-fiction.

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:43.670
She specializes in
Uruguayan poetry.

00:04:43.670 --> 00:04:48.550
Her translations include
"The invisible bridge",

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:50.160
"Selected poems of
Circe Maia" and "Fable

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:53.890
of an inconsolable man",
by Javier Echeverra.

00:04:53.890 --> 00:04:57.930
She's also editor of "America
Invertida, an anthology

00:04:57.930 --> 00:05:02.330
of emerging Uruguayan poets"
and "Earth, Water, Sky",

00:05:02.330 --> 00:05:06.590
a bilingual anthology
of environmental poetry.

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:11.020
She was a 2016 NEA
translation fellow.

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:13.900
She is the sonagale
[phonetic] professor of poetry

00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:16.740
at the University of
Wisconsin, Madison,

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:18.970
and she directs a program
in creative writing,

00:05:18.970 --> 00:05:23.760
and she might stand at this
podium more than I do today.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:29.580
Also, we have in
attendance and participating

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:33.220
with us Jeannine
Pitas, a writer, teacher

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:35.730
and Spanish English
literary translator.

00:05:35.730 --> 00:05:39.270
She's the author of two poetry
checkbooks, and the translator

00:05:39.270 --> 00:05:41.860
of several Uruguayan poets
including Selva Casal

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:43.990
and Marosa di Giorgio.

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:45.290
She's published translations

00:05:45.290 --> 00:05:49.090
of acclaimed Uruguayan writer
Marosa Di Giorgio's work.

00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:53.110
I remember "Nightfall" and
"The history of violets".

00:05:53.110 --> 00:05:59.140
She's an assistant professor
at the University of --

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:00.850
oh my gosh, Debuke,
that's what I thought,

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:04.390
and then I just flipped
at it and thought,

00:06:04.390 --> 00:06:06.100
"that sounds strange".

00:06:06.100 --> 00:06:10.470
I know. And then also we
have with us Seth Michelson,

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:13.210
who is a poet and
translator, whose collections

00:06:13.210 --> 00:06:15.560
of poetry include
"Swimming through fire",

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:19.380
"Eyes like broken windows",
"Cottage for my unborn son"

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:22.160
and "Maestro of Brutal
splendor".

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:24.820
His translations include
the books "The ghetto"

00:06:24.820 --> 00:06:32.040
by Tamara Kamenszain and
Uruguayan poets Victoria Estol,

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:36.110
Oro Lipodri [phonetic] and
Melissa Machado, "The red hour".

00:06:36.110 --> 00:06:38.530
He currently teaches the
poetry of the Americas

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:40.530
at Washington and
Lee University.

00:06:40.530 --> 00:06:45.590
Thank you all for being
here, and I look forward

00:06:45.590 --> 00:06:47.890
to hearing everyone else speak.

00:06:53.510 --> 00:07:06.830
[ Applause ]

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:08.540
&gt;&gt; Jesse Lee Kercheval:
Thank you so much for coming.

00:07:08.540 --> 00:07:10.620
This is a great privilege
and honor.

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:12.970
I want to thank everyone at the
Hispanic division who has been

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:17.030
so supportive of my work,
and Rob Casper and people

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:19.930
in the Port Lloyd's office,
and the Uruguayan Embassy,

00:07:19.930 --> 00:07:22.000
and all of Washington DC --

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.060
well, maybe not all of
Washington DC [laughter].

00:07:26.060 --> 00:07:28.260
I wanted just to
say a little bit

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:30.120
about why this is a celebration

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:32.970
of Uruguayan women's
poetry and why --

00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:37.800
I'm so obsessed with it.

00:07:37.800 --> 00:07:41.220
It's a tradition that's
just amazing to me.

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:44.690
Uruguay is a country
of 3.3 million people,

00:07:44.690 --> 00:07:47.580
the smallest Spanish speaking
country in Latin America.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:49.450
It's a country full of poets.

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:52.650
My joke is they produce two
things in world class level

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:56.250
on super abundance, which is
the soccer players and poets,

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:59.250
but besides that, it has a
long tradition of poetry.

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:02.920
But it has this really amazing
tradition of poetry by women.

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:05.360
And this is important in
an era where, even now,

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:07.740
I'd buy a great,
big, fat anthology

00:08:07.740 --> 00:08:11.700
of Latin American
poetry, edited by people

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:13.500
who they really know what
they're doing, and there are two

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:15.920
or three women poets
in the whole thing.

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:17.680
And there are many
more good women poets

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:19.390
and that just in Uruguay.

00:08:19.390 --> 00:08:21.540
And the tradition specially
gets started at turn

00:08:21.540 --> 00:08:23.580
of the 20th century, with poets

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:28.270
like Maria Eugenia Vaz
Ferreira and Ramiro Agustini.

00:08:28.270 --> 00:08:30.610
And we don't start quite that
far back, but we're really going

00:08:30.610 --> 00:08:32.980
to cover quite a run
almost up to the present,

00:08:32.980 --> 00:08:35.260
and that is we're going
to have some poetry

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:36.560
by some of the poets.

00:08:36.560 --> 00:08:38.300
There's something called
"The Generation of 45",

00:08:38.300 --> 00:08:41.950
which was the great flowering
of literature in Uruguay.

00:08:41.950 --> 00:08:44.610
And we have poems
by Amanda Berenger,

00:08:44.610 --> 00:08:47.670
and there's a wonderful new
anthology of work coming out

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:52.790
and Ana Dini -- Ana -- who's
going to be reading some

00:08:52.790 --> 00:08:55.170
of her translations, it'll
be in that anthology.

00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:57.220
And [inaudible] by Idea
Vilariño, who is, again,

00:08:57.220 --> 00:08:59.390
a really essential poet
that we had a reading just

00:08:59.390 --> 00:09:00.690
of her work two years ago.

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:04.210
And then, that's the people born
in the 20s, and then you sort

00:09:04.210 --> 00:09:07.490
of jump up to people who
are born in the 1930s,

00:09:07.490 --> 00:09:10.200
we're going to have the work by
the amazing Morosa Di Giorgio

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:11.750
and Jeannine Pitas
is her translator,

00:09:11.750 --> 00:09:13.660
and it's a wonderful new
book called, I remember,

00:09:13.660 --> 00:09:14.960
"Nightfall" out of her work.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:17.690
And the poet Selva
Casal who I adore.

00:09:17.690 --> 00:09:19.830
Jeannine is just starting
to bring it to English.

00:09:19.830 --> 00:09:21.850
It's really not been
available in English before.

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:23.970
And also born in the
30s is Cirse Maia,

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:26.970
the poet that I translated
for this book from Pittsburgh,

00:09:26.970 --> 00:09:29.060
"The invisible bridge".

00:09:29.060 --> 00:09:32.630
And so, that's starting out
so, that's the 20s and the 30s,

00:09:32.630 --> 00:09:34.850
and then we move forward
to Silva, who is a --

00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:37.260
you know, a several
decades ahead,

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:40.440
and right now we're just really
privileged to have her with us.

00:09:40.440 --> 00:09:42.730
She's really one of the most
important living women poets

00:09:42.730 --> 00:09:45.440
in Uruguay, especially
someone who is,

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:47.030
you know, of her generation.

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:49.440
I'd just have to say Ida
Vitale who is in the generation

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:50.740
of the 20s is still alive.

00:09:50.740 --> 00:09:52.550
Uruguayan women poets,
they live forever.

00:09:52.550 --> 00:09:56.820
But Silvia Guerra is really an
important Uruguayan women poet.

00:09:56.820 --> 00:09:58.510
And she's really been
at the center of poetry,

00:09:58.510 --> 00:10:00.460
which she works in poetry
foundation, she's worked

00:10:00.460 --> 00:10:03.430
for presses, she's doing
interviewing poetry,

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:05.060
really works hard to move
forward this tradition.

00:10:05.060 --> 00:10:09.620
And Jeannine Pitas -- and I will
be reading translations of hers.

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:11.090
We've just started
translating her work.

00:10:11.090 --> 00:10:12.910
And then to close or sort,

00:10:12.910 --> 00:10:15.790
the youngest person
will be Melissa Machado,

00:10:15.790 --> 00:10:18.280
who is just in her 40s

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:20.610
and Michaels Seth
translated her book

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:23.120
which she was published
here last year.

00:10:23.120 --> 00:10:25.550
Now, we won't be reading in
that order, we're reading

00:10:25.550 --> 00:10:26.980
in the order that's in the
program, but I just wanted

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:29.080
to give you a sense of the
sweep, from people born

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:33.040
in the 1920s, to
people born, you know,

00:10:33.040 --> 00:10:34.570
just at the end of
the last century.

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:36.160
And, really if we wanted
to and we have time,

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:37.460
we can go all the
way down to poets

00:10:37.460 --> 00:10:40.500
who are publishing books now and
being discovered in anthologies

00:10:40.500 --> 00:10:43.610
in Uruguay who are
in their 17, 18, 22.

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:46.140
It's just this constant
flowering

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.170
of Uruguayan women
poets, and this tradition

00:10:48.170 --> 00:10:51.450
that makes each woman aware of
the possibility of being a poet.

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:52.750
And I'm talking about
being serious,

00:10:52.750 --> 00:10:55.300
well-known public intellectual,
not someone, you know,

00:10:55.300 --> 00:10:58.010
who writes secretly and it's
discovered after they're gone.

00:10:58.010 --> 00:11:00.410
So, I really feel
this is something

00:11:00.410 --> 00:11:02.150
that should be better
known outside of Uruguay,

00:11:02.150 --> 00:11:04.420
and I hope you feel the same
way after you hear the poetry.

00:11:04.420 --> 00:11:06.510
Thank you.

00:11:06.510 --> 00:11:27.590
[ Applause ]

00:11:27.590 --> 00:11:29.890
&gt;&gt; ¿Está bien?

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:34.360
&gt;&gt; Silvia Guerra: ¿Ahí sí?

00:11:34.360 --> 00:11:37.490
Bueno, buenas tardes.

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:45.150
Estoy muy contenta
de estar acá.

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:53.640
Esto que voy a leer se llama
"Ese espacio que es mío".

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:58.510
Este libro es un libro que
salió en Buenos Aires.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:07.380
Para nosotros es importante
decirlo porque el Río de la

00:12:07.380 --> 00:12:13.530
Plata funciona un poco como
Río de la Plata entonces,

00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:19.340
para el Uruguay Buenos
Aires es muy importante.

00:12:19.340 --> 00:12:30.290
Somos como una especie
también de región, ¿no?

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:32.880
El Río de la Plata.

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:43.010
Este libro salió en Buenos
Aires en una editorial que la

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:50.500
llevan adelante tres poetas
mujeres que se llaman Dolores

00:12:50.500 --> 00:12:58.460
Echecopar, María Mascheroni
y María del Carmen Colombo.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:05.550
Y me gusta nombrarlas porque
me parece que está bien.

00:13:05.550 --> 00:13:12.880
Siempre le tengo que agradecer
a Jesse todo lo que ha hecho con

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:18.090
la traducción y bueno,
a Jeannine, pero digo,

00:13:18.090 --> 00:13:23.300
Jesse es como la persona que ha
ido al Uruguay y ha traído a

00:13:23.300 --> 00:13:25.070
los uruguayos para acá.

00:13:25.070 --> 00:13:31.800
Este poema se llama "Ese
espacio que es mío".

00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:39.080
"Ese espacio de cielo, ese
que es mío, en la palma,

00:13:39.080 --> 00:13:42.270
pedazo de arena, salvia, viento.

00:13:42.270 --> 00:13:50.190
¿Qué puede demostrar al
mundo uno o dos dientes,

00:13:50.190 --> 00:13:55.090
de sombrero ladeado,
de aguafiestas?

00:13:55.090 --> 00:13:57.340
Todo es un torbellino.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:13:59.460
El silbido del viento,

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:05.100
la claridad previa del
trueno detrás de la isla,

00:14:05.100 --> 00:14:09.430
los postibones verdes.

00:14:09.430 --> 00:14:16.600
Ese espacio de cielo, las rocas
justas que entran en la ventana,

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:18.960
Javier por la bajada,
el chorro de agua.

00:14:18.960 --> 00:14:20.850
¿Qué son ahora
uno o dos dientes?

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:22.150
¿El hincapié?

00:14:22.150 --> 00:14:23.450
¿La angustia?

00:14:23.450 --> 00:14:26.390
¿Qué son ahora los dientes de
Drácula de plástico olvidados

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:30.990
en el lavabo de un
baño que no es mío?

00:14:30.990 --> 00:14:34.690
¿Quién va a decirme
a mí lo que era mío?

00:14:34.690 --> 00:14:37.110
¿Quién va a explicarme
a mí lo que me resta?

00:14:37.110 --> 00:14:38.700
Me aguarda un paraíso de
ramas extendidas que para en

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:40.000
la caída.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:41.300
Me aguarda una arboleda,

00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:42.600
muchedumbre de árboles
juntados esperándome.

00:14:42.600 --> 00:14:43.900
Ese espacio de cielo
reservado, salvia, viento.

00:14:43.900 --> 00:14:45.200
Ese espacio de cielo,
estoy segura."

00:14:45.200 --> 00:14:46.500
&gt;&gt; Jesse Lee Kercheval: Silvia
was saying this was a book

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:47.800
of verses that was published
in Argentina last year.

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:49.100
There's a sort of
culture that Argentina

00:14:49.100 --> 00:14:50.400
and Uruguay share
Rioplatense culture.

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:51.700
And it's an anthology all
selected of her books.

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:53.000
"That space is mine, that
space of sky is mine,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:54.300
in the palm, a bit of sand.

00:14:54.300 --> 00:14:55.600
Sage, wind, what can
I show the world?

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:56.900
One or two teeth like a
tilted hat, a squeal sport.

00:14:56.900 --> 00:14:58.200
Everything is a whirlwind.

00:14:58.200 --> 00:14:59.500
The whistling wind,
the early clarity

00:14:59.500 --> 00:15:00.800
of thunder behind the
island, the green shutters.

00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:02.100
That space of sky, the precise
rocks fitting into the window.

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:03.400
Javier going down,
the jet of water.

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:04.700
What are they now?

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:06.000
One, two teeth?

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:07.300
The stress, the anguish?

00:15:07.300 --> 00:15:08.600
What are the plastic Dracula
teeth now, forgotten in the sink

00:15:08.600 --> 00:15:09.900
of a bathroom that is not mine.

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:11.200
Who is going to explain
to me what is mine?

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:12.500
Who is going to tell
me what remains for me?

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:13.800
I await a paradise of
outstretched branches that fall.

00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:15.100
I wait a grove, a stack of
trees together, waiting for me.

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:16.400
That space of private
sky, sage and wind.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:17.700
That space of sky,
I am certain".

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.000
&gt;&gt; Silvia Guerra: Esto se
llama "La copa de alabastro",

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.180
y es un conjunto
de varios poemas.

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:27.630
Este es el número uno.

00:15:27.630 --> 00:15:36.220
"Una fisura se tiñe con la
niebla que inicia en la llanura.

00:15:36.220 --> 00:15:41.790
Verde del jade oblicuo que da
la transparencia que es medada.

00:15:41.790 --> 00:15:48.170
Hojas de espeso tinte,
aroma que desciende.

00:15:48.170 --> 00:15:52.070
Fragor de ese principio
como vacuo,

00:15:52.070 --> 00:15:58.270
condena desde el tinte al
aroma, durazno que recubre.

00:15:58.270 --> 00:16:01.770
Sonrosa la línea
y va sonriendo.

00:16:01.770 --> 00:16:04.590
Pide de su dulzor
al cardenal azul.

00:16:04.590 --> 00:16:07.530
Cardenalicio moretón de celo.

00:16:07.530 --> 00:16:15.280
Rosa en la ventana del espanto
el azul tinte, de morada medusa.

00:16:15.280 --> 00:16:20.150
No mora donde acusa
y va de luto.

00:16:20.150 --> 00:16:24.920
Golpeando la cabeza
contra el vidrio,

00:16:24.920 --> 00:16:32.020
el roto cardenal abre de
rosas la cumbre del brazo.

00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:36.510
La curva que la dicha
no quisiera.

00:16:36.510 --> 00:16:50.940
Es tarde. Deben abandonarlo todo
con sangre entre los dientes.

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:59.150
Con el espeso aroma de las
hojas humeantes de la niebla.

00:16:59.150 --> 00:17:01.830
Batirse en retirada a duelo,

00:17:01.830 --> 00:17:09.230
sobre las alas de ese inmenso
albatros disecado colgando desde

00:17:09.230 --> 00:17:10.900
el techo del sepulcro.

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:13.320
Dorada bóveda de brillos,

00:17:13.320 --> 00:17:17.990
blandir en el trasluz del
fuego la mano echada en aguas,

00:17:17.990 --> 00:17:20.190
soñar de crisantemos.

00:17:20.190 --> 00:17:24.270
Al levantar el mando
que es la niebla,

00:17:24.270 --> 00:17:28.730
está la espejada de
luz con manantial,

00:17:28.730 --> 00:17:30.740
el fruto de la aurora.

00:17:30.740 --> 00:17:34.110
Tajo en la frente
mórbida, sombría,

00:17:34.110 --> 00:17:37.290
eje de evanescencia,
distraído."

00:17:37.290 --> 00:17:39.850
&gt;&gt; Jeannine Pitas: This is
called "The alabaster cup",

00:17:39.850 --> 00:17:43.500
and it's a series of a few
poems, this is the first one.

00:17:43.500 --> 00:17:49.070
"A crack is stained with fog
that begins on the flat plane.

00:17:49.070 --> 00:17:51.190
Green from the oblique jade,

00:17:51.190 --> 00:17:57.580
that gives transparency,
also negates it.

00:17:57.580 --> 00:18:00.180
Leaves of thick dye,
aroma that falls,

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:02.490
clamoring at the
somewhat empty start.

00:18:02.490 --> 00:18:05.340
Condemnation from the dye to
the aroma, peach that covers.

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:08.280
The line blushes and smiles,
asks for its sweetness

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:12.050
of the blue bruise,
bruise of jealousy.

00:18:12.050 --> 00:18:17.360
Rose in the window of fear, the
blue dye of purple jellyfish.

00:18:17.360 --> 00:18:20.590
Doesn't live where he
accuses and mourns.

00:18:20.590 --> 00:18:22.710
Banging his head
against the glass,

00:18:22.710 --> 00:18:25.600
the broken bruise opens the
roses, the curve of the arm,

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:26.900
the curve that happiness
wouldn't want.

00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:28.200
It is late, they
must leave everything

00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:29.500
with blood between their teeth.

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:30.800
With the thick aroma of
leaves damp from the fog.

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:32.100
To be beat the retreat
from a duel, on the wings

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:33.400
of that immense stuffed
albatross,

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:34.700
handing from the
sealing of the tomb.

00:18:34.700 --> 00:18:36.000
Gilded vault of shackles,

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:37.300
brandishing in the
hand the light

00:18:37.300 --> 00:18:38.600
of the fire made of petty coats.

00:18:38.600 --> 00:18:39.900
Dreaming of chrysanthemums

00:18:39.900 --> 00:18:41.200
by lifting the cloak
that is the fog.

00:18:41.200 --> 00:18:42.500
There's the translucency
of light with spring.

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:43.800
The fruit of the dawn, a cut
on the morbid forehead, somber,

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:45.100
axis of evanescence,
distracted".

00:18:45.100 --> 00:18:46.590
&gt;&gt; Silvia Guerra:
Esto se llama "Cloto".

00:18:46.590 --> 00:18:51.440
"Afuera, en el cóncavo
espejo que es ahora,

00:18:51.440 --> 00:19:00.300
un fino entretejido se suspende.

00:19:00.300 --> 00:19:08.190
Alguien habla de dos,
otros de cifras que son

00:19:08.190 --> 00:19:11.220
inmensas cantidades.

00:19:11.220 --> 00:19:20.870
La ascendencia se pierde
en estratos que no tienen

00:19:20.870 --> 00:19:24.550
demasiada importancia.

00:19:24.550 --> 00:19:31.030
Se nombran los caminos, los
pasos, los pequeños jilgueros.

00:19:31.030 --> 00:19:40.010
Se camina sonriendo por la
empinada cuesta con las botas

00:19:40.010 --> 00:19:41.590
sucias del barro del camino.

00:19:41.590 --> 00:19:44.490
Se llenan los carrillos,
los rojos, los sonrientes,

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:46.620
de un aire que allá arriba
se dice que es purísimo.

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:48.060
Y se habla de la guerra,
del color de la guerra,

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:49.590
y aparecen los muertos en
fila con el plato vacío.

00:19:49.590 --> 00:19:50.890
Me preguntan algo
que no entiendo.

00:19:50.890 --> 00:19:52.190
No entiendo qué me dicen,

00:19:52.190 --> 00:19:53.490
no entiendo qué hago
ahí, por qué me siguen.

00:19:53.490 --> 00:19:54.790
Yo no sé qué hacer
y ellos tampoco".

00:19:54.790 --> 00:19:56.090
&gt;&gt; Jesse Lee Kercheval:
This poem is titled "Cloto".

00:19:56.090 --> 00:19:57.390
It's one of the great figures
who measures out the thread,

00:19:57.390 --> 00:19:58.690
gives you the length
of your life.

00:19:58.690 --> 00:19:59.990
"Cloto. Outside in the
concave mirror that is now,

00:19:59.990 --> 00:20:01.290
a fine interweaving
is suspended.

00:20:01.290 --> 00:20:02.590
Someone speaks of two, other
figures of immense quantities.

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:05.090
The lineage gets lost on layers
that don't hold much importance.

00:20:05.090 --> 00:20:09.720
Paths, country houses, little
gold finches are named.

00:20:09.720 --> 00:20:12.860
He walks smiling down the
steep slope with boots dirty

00:20:12.860 --> 00:20:15.200
from the mud of the road.

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:19.490
The cheeks, the red, the smiling
are filled with the air that way

00:20:19.490 --> 00:20:21.760
up there they say is so pure.

00:20:21.760 --> 00:20:25.670
And they talk of war,
of the color of war,

00:20:25.670 --> 00:20:29.620
and the dead appear in line
with their empty plates.

00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:32.230
They ask me for something
I don't understand.

00:20:32.230 --> 00:20:34.770
I don't understand what
they're saying to me,

00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:37.080
I don't understand
what I'm doing here,

00:20:37.080 --> 00:20:39.290
why they are following me.

00:20:39.290 --> 00:20:42.960
And I don't know what to do,
and they don't know either".

00:20:48.240 --> 00:20:51.880
&gt;&gt; Silvia Guerra:
"La esperanza".

00:20:51.880 --> 00:21:02.580
"Siempre, como un punto
blanco y arrasante.

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:05.870
Una luz de pura esencia
necesaria, incandescente.

00:21:05.870 --> 00:21:09.860
Cegada por la luz,
la boca abierta,

00:21:09.860 --> 00:21:12.830
palpita algo en el
valle, ruido de agua,

00:21:12.830 --> 00:21:16.030
hojas de eucalipto perfumado.

00:21:16.030 --> 00:21:22.590
Algo de paz se recoge
sobre el oro esparcido.

00:21:22.590 --> 00:21:25.020
Algo parecido a la
misericordia queda"

00:21:25.020 --> 00:21:26.320
&gt;&gt; Jeannine Pitas: "Hope".

00:21:26.320 --> 00:21:27.620
"Always, like a white and
devastating point of light,

00:21:27.620 --> 00:21:32.600
of pure essential
essence, incandescent.

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:38.460
Blinded by light, open mouth,
something throbs in the valley.

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:43.870
Noise of water, leaves
of perfumed eucalyptus.

00:21:43.870 --> 00:21:48.250
Some peace gathers on
the scattered gold,

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:52.730
something similar
to mercy remains".

00:22:00.730 --> 00:22:03.030
&gt;&gt; Silvia Guerra: Bueno,
esta es la última.

00:22:03.030 --> 00:22:06.670
Bueno, les agradezco de vuelta.

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:10.050
Le agradezco mucho a Jesse
y a todos los traductores,

00:22:10.050 --> 00:22:15.700
porque yo creo que así
es como se hace la vida.

00:22:15.700 --> 00:22:21.380
Esto tiene un número
que es el número 32.

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:28.480
"En la otra punta de la línea
se balancea la impotencia,

00:22:28.480 --> 00:22:33.540
pero en medio está todo.

00:22:33.540 --> 00:22:38.600
Pugnando por su forma imposible,

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:43.580
acumulándose en el
producimiento interminable.

00:22:43.580 --> 00:22:52.830
Se huele, se oye un ruido de
fondo que acelera su pulso.

00:22:52.830 --> 00:23:07.670
Emerge de los sueños mezclada
con la niebla en jirones,

00:23:07.670 --> 00:23:16.580
crujiendo de asombro
en la penumbra.

00:23:16.580 --> 00:23:30.810
Acunada, y el diálogo
amoroso que descansa en la paz

00:23:32.300 --> 00:23:33.600
del laurel.

00:23:33.600 --> 00:23:38.240
Preferís el mes de tierra
removida como marca el recuerdo,

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:45.540
y esa voz que se escucha en
los andenes de alta velocidad

00:23:45.540 --> 00:23:51.080
repite, 'no te creas',
'no te creas',

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:54.430
'no te creas', 'no te creas'.

00:23:54.430 --> 00:23:57.210
Se sostiene porque la sola vida,

00:23:57.210 --> 00:24:01.450
la sola manera de estar
vivo ha dictado esa cifra,

00:24:01.450 --> 00:24:06.530
que gotea en la especificidad
del tramo.

00:24:06.530 --> 00:24:12.380
Aparece en los ojos la
perdición justo cuando la

00:24:12.380 --> 00:24:14.140
enfermedad daba la vuelta.

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:19.090
La proyección tira del
halo más allá, que jala.

00:24:19.090 --> 00:24:20.390
Ya nadie sabrá nada.

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:25.380
Solamente retumba en los
andenes al compás del zumbido,

00:24:25.380 --> 00:24:26.900
y parece que dice 'chajá',
'chajá', 'chajá'".

00:24:26.900 --> 00:24:28.200
&gt;&gt; Jesse Lee Kercheval:
A note for the word

00:24:28.200 --> 00:24:29.500
at the end of this poem.

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:30.800
"Chajá", which is the name of
a bird, a large bird indigenous

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:32.100
to Uruguay, it has
a very loud sound.

00:24:32.100 --> 00:24:33.400
If you want to know what
it really sounds like,

00:24:33.400 --> 00:24:34.700
you have to Google the words
"screaming chicken" [laughter].

00:24:34.700 --> 00:24:36.000
"On the other end of the line
balances the helplessness,

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:37.300
in the middle is everything.

00:24:37.300 --> 00:24:38.600
Fighting for its
impossible form, accumulating

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:39.900
in ceaseless production,
you smell,

00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:41.200
you hear the background noise
which quickens its pulse.

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:42.500
It emerges from dreams
mixed with tatters of fog,

00:24:42.500 --> 00:24:43.800
squeaking with astonishment
in the half life.

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:45.100
Rocking and loving dialogue
rests on peace laurels.

00:24:45.100 --> 00:24:46.400
You prefer the month of plowed
earth as marked by memory

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:47.700
and that voice that's
heard on the high speed

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:49.000
of platforms repeating, 'don't
believe it', 'don't believe it',

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:50.300
'don't believe it',
'don't believe'.

00:24:50.300 --> 00:24:51.600
It holds because the
only life, the only way

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:52.900
of being alive has
dictated that number,

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:54.200
that drips into the
specificity of the stretch.

00:24:54.200 --> 00:24:55.500
Perdition appears in the eyes,

00:24:55.500 --> 00:24:56.800
just when the illness
is taking a turn.

00:24:56.800 --> 00:24:58.100
The projection pulls
the halo further away.

00:24:58.100 --> 00:24:59.400
That tug, no one will
know anything anymore.

00:24:59.400 --> 00:25:00.700
Only the voice booming on the
platform to the beat of the hum

00:25:00.700 --> 00:25:02.000
and it seems to say,
'chajá, chajá, chajá".

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:03.800
&gt;&gt; Gracias.

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:17.290
[ Applause ]

00:25:17.290 --> 00:25:18.590
&gt;&gt; Suzanne Schadl: Thank you.

00:25:18.590 --> 00:25:21.720
I omitted one person when I
was introducing the others so,

00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:23.430
if our other translators
could come up,

00:25:23.430 --> 00:25:27.680
I'd like to introduce
another one.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:31.070
Anna Deeny Morales,
is with us also today.

00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:33.000
She's translated
several collections

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:34.780
of Raul Zurita's poetry,

00:25:34.780 --> 00:25:38.990
including "Purgatory"
and "Sky bellow".

00:25:38.990 --> 00:25:41.560
Other translations
include "Floating lanterns"

00:25:41.560 --> 00:25:45.640
by Mercedes Roffe [phonetic],
as well has her translations

00:25:45.640 --> 00:25:49.350
of Alejandra Pizarnik,
which are included

00:25:49.350 --> 00:25:51.790
in "Pinholes in the night".

00:25:51.790 --> 00:25:55.290
Enter translations of the
Uruguayan poet Amanda Berenger.

00:25:55.290 --> 00:25:57.750
She's a translator and
adjunct professor at the Center

00:25:57.750 --> 00:25:59.050
for Latin American Studies

00:25:59.050 --> 00:26:01.710
at Georgetown University
just down the road.

00:26:01.710 --> 00:26:04.510
So, thank you, Ana.

00:26:04.510 --> 00:26:10.010
[ Applause ]

00:26:10.010 --> 00:26:13.750
&gt;&gt; Anna Deeny: Thank
you so much to Suzanne

00:26:13.750 --> 00:26:16.850
for receiving us here
today, Catalina Gomez,

00:26:16.850 --> 00:26:20.760
Jesse first of all for
organizing this beautiful event,

00:26:20.760 --> 00:26:25.160
the Hispanic division and the
people of poetry and literature.

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:28.340
And thanks to all of you
for taking the time to come

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:30.370
out here today, it's
great to see you all.

00:26:30.370 --> 00:26:34.530
So, I'm going to read four
poems by Amanda Berenger

00:26:34.530 --> 00:26:38.440
and one poem by Idea Vilariño.

00:26:38.440 --> 00:26:43.820
Amanda Berenger was born in
1921 and she died in 2020.

00:26:43.820 --> 00:26:48.830
She was a prolific poet of
the "Generación del 45",

00:26:48.830 --> 00:26:50.860
and like many of
her contemporaries,

00:26:50.860 --> 00:26:54.220
Berenger's poetry often
represents meaning under siege.

00:26:54.220 --> 00:26:55.740
She wrote this book
that I'll read

00:26:55.740 --> 00:26:58.110
from during the Uruguayan
dictatorship,

00:26:58.110 --> 00:27:03.200
which was from 1973 to 1985.

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:06.470
So, this is from the
identity of certain fruits,

00:27:06.470 --> 00:27:08.340
"la identidad de
ciertas frutas",

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:12.790
which was published in 1982.

00:27:12.790 --> 00:27:16.930
"Uno, la manzana.

00:27:16.930 --> 00:27:21.170
Con las manzanas
deliciosamente conozco el deseo,

00:27:21.170 --> 00:27:26.040
descubro la salud, y esa larva
de muerte que se lleva en medio

00:27:26.040 --> 00:27:28.030
del esplendor.

00:27:28.030 --> 00:27:31.870
Ser como la manzana
implica todas las culpas,

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:34.850
pero es excitante la propuesta.

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:38.890
La manzana es brillante
y peligrosa.

00:27:38.890 --> 00:27:43.000
Una sola puede incendiar
un huerto.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:48.550
Ser como la manzana es estar
en la alta fiesta del día,

00:27:48.550 --> 00:27:51.290
toda de lazo rojo y diamantes,

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:59.810
y llevar en el índice
enguantado un anillo de sombra".

00:27:59.810 --> 00:28:03.600
"One, the apple.

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:07.960
By way of apples deliciously
I come upon desire.

00:28:07.960 --> 00:28:12.250
Discover, wellbeing, and
that larva of death folded

00:28:12.250 --> 00:28:15.340
in the midst of splendor.

00:28:15.340 --> 00:28:21.950
To be as the apple involves all
fault, but the proposal thrills.

00:28:21.950 --> 00:28:25.220
The apple is brilliant
and dangerous.

00:28:25.220 --> 00:28:28.780
One alone can flame an orchard.

00:28:28.780 --> 00:28:33.930
To be as the apple is to be
at the high dance of day,

00:28:33.930 --> 00:28:36.280
all red satin and diamonds

00:28:36.280 --> 00:28:43.980
and on a gloved finger
wear, a ring of dusk".

00:28:43.980 --> 00:28:47.430
"Nine -- nueve, los higos.

00:28:49.490 --> 00:28:52.970
Tiene sangre el fruto
de la higuera,

00:28:52.970 --> 00:29:00.610
y destila su néctar tenaz, su
culposo jarabe, sigilosamente.

00:29:00.610 --> 00:29:02.900
Ha habido un crimen,

00:29:02.900 --> 00:29:06.970
una violación bajo
las grandes hojas.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:11.460
Yo observaba, embebida
a través de las ramas.

00:29:11.460 --> 00:29:15.760
Los higos cuelgan maduros,
amoratados, remordimientos.

00:29:15.760 --> 00:29:21.610
Los higos cuelgan del árbol
como murciélagos de melaza,

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:28.690
como ahorcados por robar
un manojo de lujuria".

00:29:28.690 --> 00:29:31.090
"Nine, the figs.

00:29:31.090 --> 00:29:34.450
The fig trees' fruit
holds blood,

00:29:34.450 --> 00:29:36.740
and distills its
tenacious nectar,

00:29:36.740 --> 00:29:40.090
its guilty syrup
surreptitiously.

00:29:40.090 --> 00:29:45.290
A crime was committed, a
violation under the wide leaves.

00:29:45.290 --> 00:29:48.770
I watched, drunk
through the branches.

00:29:48.770 --> 00:29:52.360
The ripe figs hang black
and blue of regrets.

00:29:52.360 --> 00:29:56.710
Figs hang from the tree,
like molasses bats,

00:29:56.710 --> 00:30:00.970
like people hanged for
robbing a fistful of lust".

00:30:05.110 --> 00:30:07.780
"18, las guindas".

00:30:07.780 --> 00:30:10.970
A Marosa Di Giorgio.

00:30:10.970 --> 00:30:16.080
"De las guindas guardo su
retrato, su pintura ardiente,

00:30:16.080 --> 00:30:20.160
el rincón vivo de
una naturaleza muerta.

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:24.610
Su vibrante vocación
de licoristas.

00:30:24.610 --> 00:30:28.640
Guardo su retrato
protegido por el vidrio.

00:30:28.640 --> 00:30:33.820
Desde los frascos labrados,
desde las sombreadas alas,

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:37.510
desde los aparadores
con cristales,

00:30:37.510 --> 00:30:42.950
custodian sus pequeños senos
de púrpura prisionera en recato

00:30:42.950 --> 00:30:44.600
y arrogamiento.

00:30:44.600 --> 00:30:49.940
Las visitas no beben
ya guindado,

00:30:49.940 --> 00:30:52.870
las visitas no son visitas.

00:30:52.870 --> 00:30:56.700
Las tías y las amigas de las
tías tienen en la mano una

00:30:56.700 --> 00:30:59.000
copita vacía".

00:31:01.270 --> 00:31:06.590
"18, the cherries"
for Marosa Di Giorgio.

00:31:06.590 --> 00:31:13.640
"Of cherries I keep her
image, her fervent paint,

00:31:13.640 --> 00:31:17.230
the living alcove
of a still life.

00:31:17.230 --> 00:31:20.610
The vibrant call of distillers.

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:24.340
I keep her image
safeguarded by the glass.

00:31:24.340 --> 00:31:28.350
From ornamented jars,
from shaded halls,

00:31:28.350 --> 00:31:31.970
for the credenza cabinet
displays they look

00:31:31.970 --> 00:31:36.030
after her small breasts
purple prisoner

00:31:36.030 --> 00:31:40.090
in restraint and rapture.

00:31:40.090 --> 00:31:44.140
Guests no longer
drink cherry liquor.

00:31:44.140 --> 00:31:47.310
Guests are not who
they used to be.

00:31:47.310 --> 00:31:48.890
The aunts and the friends

00:31:48.890 --> 00:31:56.000
of the aunts each hold a
cordial, and it's empty".

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.870
"20, las castañas dos".

00:31:58.870 --> 00:32:05.350
"En otras ramas del árbol
renacen otras castañas.

00:32:05.350 --> 00:32:08.000
Estamos en Montevideo.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.100
Verano u otoño quizás.

00:32:11.100 --> 00:32:13.970
Miro una evanescente
bombonería,

00:32:13.970 --> 00:32:18.890
miro las hojas de espejo
con iniciales detrás,

00:32:18.890 --> 00:32:25.220
en su caja maleada de festón y
puntillas, están los capullos,

00:32:25.220 --> 00:32:30.600
los cofres, bajo un
blanco pétalo glaseado.

00:32:30.600 --> 00:32:33.360
La bella durmiente del bosque,

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:37.070
la princesa extranjera
Majón Glasé,

00:32:37.070 --> 00:32:41.180
serenísimas y lujosas
crisálidas.

00:32:41.180 --> 00:32:45.660
Entonces, vuela una extraviada
imagen, las castañas desnudas,

00:32:45.660 --> 00:32:51.600
cubiertas de plata
resplandecen imposibles".

00:32:51.600 --> 00:32:56.410
"20, the chestnuts two.

00:32:56.410 --> 00:33:04.430
On other branches of the tree
other chestnuts are born again.

00:33:04.430 --> 00:33:06.950
We're in Montevideo.

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:09.860
Maybe summer or fall.

00:33:09.860 --> 00:33:13.150
I see an evanescent candy store.

00:33:13.150 --> 00:33:16.500
I see the initial
mirrored leaves.

00:33:16.500 --> 00:33:21.620
Behind in her box lined with
festoon and point lace, there,

00:33:21.620 --> 00:33:23.520
the bugs, the treasures.

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:27.780
Below a white glassed petal.

00:33:27.780 --> 00:33:30.310
The sleeping beauty
of the woods,

00:33:30.310 --> 00:33:34.740
the foreign princess
Majón Glasé, such serene

00:33:34.740 --> 00:33:38.140
and luxuriant chrysalises.

00:33:38.140 --> 00:33:42.500
Then a lost image glides through
the air, the naked chestnuts,

00:33:42.500 --> 00:33:48.380
covered in silver, they
resplend impossibly".

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:53.230
And this poem is
by Idea Vilariño

00:33:53.230 --> 00:33:57.960
who was born a year before
Amanda Berenger in 1920,

00:33:57.960 --> 00:34:01.920
and died a year before
Amanda Berenger in 2009,

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:06.700
also from la "Generación del
45", the generation of 45.

00:34:06.700 --> 00:34:08.970
This was published
in an anthology

00:34:08.970 --> 00:34:11.850
of Latin American poetry
selected by Raul Zurita,

00:34:11.850 --> 00:34:15.070
edited by Forest Gander and it's
called "Pinholes in the night",

00:34:15.070 --> 00:34:17.370
published by Copper Cannon.

00:34:18.380 --> 00:34:22.440
"Ya no. Ya no será.

00:34:22.440 --> 00:34:29.060
Ya no, no viviremos juntos,
no criaré a tu hijo.

00:34:29.060 --> 00:34:32.970
No coseré tu ropa, no
te tendré de noche,

00:34:32.970 --> 00:34:36.170
no te besaré al irme,
nunca sabrás quién fui,

00:34:36.170 --> 00:34:39.060
por qué me amaron otros.

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:42.490
No llegaré a saber por
qué ni cómo nunca,

00:34:42.490 --> 00:34:46.530
ni si era verdad lo que dijiste
que era ni quién fuiste ni

00:34:46.530 --> 00:34:53.330
quién fui para ti, ni cómo
hubiera sido vivir juntos.

00:34:53.330 --> 00:34:56.970
Querernos, esperarnos, estar.

00:34:56.970 --> 00:35:03.650
Ya no soy más que yo para
siempre y tú ya no serás para

00:35:03.650 --> 00:35:04.950
mí más que tú.

00:35:04.950 --> 00:35:08.260
Ya no estás en un día futuro.

00:35:08.260 --> 00:35:14.810
No sabré dónde vives, con
quién ni si te acuerdas.

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:18.060
No me abrazarás nunca
como esa noche, nunca.

00:35:18.060 --> 00:35:22.570
No volveré a tocarte.

00:35:22.570 --> 00:35:24.100
No te veré morir".

00:35:24.100 --> 00:35:28.940
"Not any more.

00:35:28.940 --> 00:35:32.270
This won't be, not anymore.

00:35:32.270 --> 00:35:35.820
We won't live together,
I won't raise your son.

00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:40.090
I won't sew your clothes,
I won't have you at night.

00:35:40.090 --> 00:35:42.510
I won't kiss you as I leave.

00:35:42.510 --> 00:35:47.390
You'll never know who I
was, why others loved me.

00:35:47.390 --> 00:35:50.470
I will never know
why or how ever,

00:35:50.470 --> 00:35:54.380
or if it was even true what you
said it was or who you were,

00:35:54.380 --> 00:35:58.040
or who I was for you, or
how it might have been

00:35:58.040 --> 00:36:00.080
to live together.

00:36:00.080 --> 00:36:06.780
To love one another, to
wait for each other, to be.

00:36:06.780 --> 00:36:09.200
I no longer more than I forever,

00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:13.850
and you won't be any
more than you for me.

00:36:13.850 --> 00:36:16.990
You're no longer
in a future day.

00:36:16.990 --> 00:36:22.490
I won't know where you live with
who, or if you even remember.

00:36:22.490 --> 00:36:25.080
You'll never hold me
like that night, never.

00:36:25.080 --> 00:36:29.050
I will never touch you again.

00:36:29.050 --> 00:36:31.710
I won't see you die".

00:36:31.710 --> 00:36:33.510
Gracias.

00:36:33.510 --> 00:36:44.870
