00:42:59.060 --> 00:43:01.120
&gt;&gt; Jeannine Pitas:
"I remember nightfall

00:43:01.120 --> 00:43:06.040
and the varooms open door
through which neighbors

00:43:06.040 --> 00:43:09.710
and angels came in,
and the clouds,

00:43:09.710 --> 00:43:15.090
November evening clouds drifting
in circles over the land.

00:43:15.090 --> 00:43:18.910
The little trees burden
with jasmine, with doves

00:43:18.910 --> 00:43:21.070
and droplets of water.

00:43:21.070 --> 00:43:25.010
That joyous pealing,
that endless chirping,

00:43:25.010 --> 00:43:27.440
every evening the same.

00:43:27.440 --> 00:43:29.080
And then, the next morning,

00:43:29.080 --> 00:43:33.550
with its tiny dead angles thrown
everywhere like paper birds,

00:43:33.550 --> 00:43:36.110
or the most exquisite
of eggshells.

00:43:36.110 --> 00:43:39.890
Your dazzling death".

00:43:39.890 --> 00:43:44.590
This is Marosa Di Giorgio
who lived from 1932 to 2004.

00:43:44.590 --> 00:43:49.410
All of these poems were
published in the 1960s and 1970s

00:43:49.410 --> 00:43:52.390
in Spanish originally.

00:43:52.390 --> 00:43:55.100
"That summer the
grapes were blue.

00:43:55.100 --> 00:43:59.630
Each one big, smooth,
without facets.

00:43:59.630 --> 00:44:02.950
They were totally
strange, fabulous,

00:44:02.950 --> 00:44:06.480
shining with an awful
blue brilliance.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:09.390
On the paths through the
vines you could hear them,

00:44:09.390 --> 00:44:12.880
growing with the deep,
outrageous murmur.

00:44:12.880 --> 00:44:17.280
And in the air there was
always the perfume of violets.

00:44:17.280 --> 00:44:21.330
Even the plants which were not
grapevines produced grapes.

00:44:21.330 --> 00:44:24.130
Butterflies came
from all directions,

00:44:24.130 --> 00:44:26.860
the most absurd,
the most unusual.

00:44:26.860 --> 00:44:30.520
From the four cardinal points
came the forest roosters

00:44:30.520 --> 00:44:34.280
with their wide wings,
their heads of pure gold.

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:38.010
My father dared to kill a
few of them and got rich.

00:44:38.010 --> 00:44:41.340
But grapes were bursting
out from everywhere.

00:44:41.340 --> 00:44:45.690
A big, rough, blue bunch even
emerged from the wardrobe,

00:44:45.690 --> 00:44:51.010
ancient wood, and lasted
forever like a poet.

00:44:51.010 --> 00:44:56.670
The gladiolas it's a spear, its
edge loaded with carnations,

00:44:56.670 --> 00:44:58.950
a knife of carnations.

00:44:58.950 --> 00:45:02.570
It jumps through the
window, kneels on the table.

00:45:02.570 --> 00:45:07.040
It's a vagrant flame, burning
up our papers, our dresses.

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:10.020
Mama swears that a
dead man has risen.

00:45:10.020 --> 00:45:14.010
She mentions her father and
mother and starts to cry.

00:45:14.010 --> 00:45:17.370
The pink gladiolas
opened up in our house,

00:45:17.370 --> 00:45:20.210
but scare it off, tell it to go.

00:45:20.210 --> 00:45:23.670
That crazy lily is
going to kill us.

00:45:23.670 --> 00:45:30.440
Last night it came
back again, the shadow.

00:45:30.440 --> 00:45:33.260
Even though 100 years
had passed,

00:45:33.260 --> 00:45:35.590
we recognized it immediately.

00:45:35.590 --> 00:45:38.090
It floated past the
guardian of violets,

00:45:38.090 --> 00:45:40.000
the bedroom, the kitchen.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:44.130
It circled around the syrup
jars, the plates white as bones,

00:45:44.130 --> 00:45:46.430
the syrup jars that
smelled like roses.

00:45:46.430 --> 00:45:49.160
It went back to the bedroom,

00:45:49.160 --> 00:45:52.480
interrupted lovemaking,
embraces.

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:55.510
Those who were awake
lay with fixed eyes,

00:45:55.510 --> 00:45:58.610
those who were sleeping,
still saw it.

00:45:58.610 --> 00:46:00.950
The mirror in which
it either saw itself,

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:04.580
or didn't see itself,
collapsed and shattered.

00:46:04.580 --> 00:46:07.780
It seemed like it
wanted to kill someone,

00:46:07.780 --> 00:46:10.400
but then it floated
out to the garden.

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:14.040
It was spinning,
digging in the same spot,

00:46:14.040 --> 00:46:17.480
as if there were a
corpse buried beneath.

00:46:17.480 --> 00:46:22.430
The poor cow grazing close
to the violets went crazy.

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:25.810
She groaned like a
woman or like a wolf.

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:29.600
But the shadow took off
flying, off towards the south.

00:46:29.600 --> 00:46:33.340
It will return within
a century".

00:46:33.340 --> 00:46:35.160
I'm still happy to hear
some of you laughing.

00:46:35.160 --> 00:46:36.960
Di Giorgio's meant to be funny.

00:46:36.960 --> 00:46:40.020
And I mean, if you
heard her read it --

00:46:40.020 --> 00:46:43.860
I mean, yes, I would read one
in Spanish but in the interest

00:46:43.860 --> 00:46:49.530
of time I will just read one
more poem by another poet

00:46:49.530 --> 00:46:53.910
from her generation, Selva
Casal, who was born possibly

00:46:53.910 --> 00:46:57.170
in 1929, possibly in the 1930s,

00:46:57.170 --> 00:46:59.250
different sources
say different things.

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:03.390
She's still living
and she won't tell me.

00:47:03.390 --> 00:47:11.580
So, she is a former penal lawyer
and professor of sociology

00:47:11.580 --> 00:47:14.310
who wrote this book during
the time of the dictatorship,

00:47:14.310 --> 00:47:16.650
and lost her job before it.

00:47:16.650 --> 00:47:21.500
So, you know, some people paid
with more than that for standing

00:47:21.500 --> 00:47:24.430
up for what they believed,
but she still paid a price

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:27.120
for standing up for
what she believes

00:47:27.120 --> 00:47:30.490
and that's what I
admire about her so much.

00:47:30.490 --> 00:47:34.840
"There's no sea anymore,
there are bullets.

00:47:34.840 --> 00:47:38.640
You come back from the
wave and move forward.

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:42.730
The bullet hisses, it
hisses on the golden foam.

00:47:42.730 --> 00:47:45.820
Foam, blood, sea.

00:47:45.820 --> 00:47:50.030
Today an absurd man in
growing in your eyes.

00:47:50.030 --> 00:47:52.780
He has neither sea nor house.

00:47:52.780 --> 00:47:57.310
He's the everyday world,
violent to the point of delirium

00:47:57.310 --> 00:48:00.610
that grabs you by the
feet, snatches you,

00:48:00.610 --> 00:48:03.750
climbs up your feet
and devours you.

00:48:03.750 --> 00:48:07.420
Lays you out naked
and alone over death,

00:48:07.420 --> 00:48:10.090
over a landscape of flies.

00:48:10.090 --> 00:48:13.710
There's no sea anymore,
there are bullets.

00:48:13.710 --> 00:48:19.260
There's this world, awarded
blood, parades, assaults.

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:24.180
Later, they put on
statistician's voices and speak

00:48:24.180 --> 00:48:26.200
of a democratic system".

00:48:26.200 --> 00:48:28.000
Thank you so much.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:39.520
[ Applause ]

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:40.820
&gt;&gt; Jesse Lee Kercheval:
Thanks again.

00:48:40.820 --> 00:48:43.410
I'm going to close with
two poems by Cirse Maya,

00:48:43.410 --> 00:48:47.630
was born in the 1930s.

00:48:47.630 --> 00:48:50.300
And actually, the poem Jeannine
read set up this one very well,

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:52.060
which is that in Uruguay
the poem are written

00:48:52.060 --> 00:48:54.440
at certain period
during the dictatorship,

00:48:54.440 --> 00:48:56.250
and if you read them
knowing that,

00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:59.690
you think differently
of the poem.

00:48:59.690 --> 00:49:02.620
And so, Cirse Maia's
husband, who was a doctor,

00:49:02.620 --> 00:49:04.910
was sent to prison
during the dictatorship

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:06.710
and she didn't really know
whether she would ever see

00:49:06.710 --> 00:49:08.010
him again.

00:49:08.010 --> 00:49:10.750
This poem is called "Treason".

00:49:10.750 --> 00:49:15.940
"The last son did not say
to him 'I am the last son'.

00:49:15.940 --> 00:49:18.290
Nothing prepared him.

00:49:18.290 --> 00:49:20.320
The water spilt over his body

00:49:20.320 --> 00:49:22.190
and you didn't know
this was the way

00:49:22.190 --> 00:49:24.880
that the water said 'goodbye'.

00:49:24.880 --> 00:49:26.310
He did not know.

00:49:26.310 --> 00:49:28.160
No one told him anything.

00:49:28.160 --> 00:49:32.200
When night came, it came to
stay, and he never knew".

00:49:32.200 --> 00:49:36.370
And then we're going to read
the last poem in the book,

00:49:36.370 --> 00:49:38.830
and it's called "Invitation".

00:49:38.830 --> 00:49:41.550
And it's pretty
self-explanatory,

00:49:41.550 --> 00:49:43.360
but it also has a
backstory for me and that is

00:49:43.360 --> 00:49:48.070
when you go visit Cirse Maia,
in Uruguay, which is a country

00:49:48.070 --> 00:49:51.860
of 3.3 million people,
1.5 million live

00:49:51.860 --> 00:49:53.700
in the capital, Montevideo.

00:49:53.700 --> 00:49:56.060
Nearly all the poets
live in the capital,

00:49:56.060 --> 00:49:57.360
even if they were
born somewhere else.

00:49:57.360 --> 00:49:59.500
It has that kind of
Paris attraction.

00:49:59.500 --> 00:50:01.510
But Cirse Maia lives
in Tacuarembó,

00:50:01.510 --> 00:50:03.590
which is a five-hour bus
trip, I can tell you,

00:50:03.590 --> 00:50:06.730
having made it many times
upwards the Brazilian boarder.

00:50:06.730 --> 00:50:08.940
But when you go to visit
her, when I go to visit her,

00:50:08.940 --> 00:50:11.580
Silvia and I went to a
wonderful visit this last spring

00:50:11.580 --> 00:50:12.880
to interview her.

00:50:12.880 --> 00:50:15.760
When young poets make this
trip to her door, she takes you

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:19.030
through the house and out
to her back-wall garden

00:50:19.030 --> 00:50:21.320
to sit under her lemon tree.

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:24.130
So, if you think of that when
you have a poet address you

00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:25.640
in this palm, that would
be the right vision.

00:50:25.640 --> 00:50:27.820
And Cirse, I have to say,

00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:31.010
is the most lovely
person I've ever met.

00:50:31.010 --> 00:50:32.850
"Invitation".

00:50:32.850 --> 00:50:37.260
"I would like you to hear my
voice, wish I could hear yours.

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:39.140
Yes, yes, I'm talking to you,

00:50:39.140 --> 00:50:42.470
silent case that runs
over these lines.

00:50:42.470 --> 00:50:45.070
You disapprove, perhaps,
of this impossible desire

00:50:45.070 --> 00:50:47.190
to escape paper and ink.

00:50:47.190 --> 00:50:49.050
What would we say to each other?

00:50:49.050 --> 00:50:51.780
I don't know, but it has to be
better that when I was talking

00:50:51.780 --> 00:50:55.050
to myself, turning
phrases, sounds, placing

00:50:55.050 --> 00:50:58.370
and removing parenthesis
and putting them in again.

00:50:58.370 --> 00:51:02.100
If your voice interrupts and
breaks this very line, come in.

00:51:02.100 --> 00:51:04.350
I was waiting for you, this way.

00:51:04.350 --> 00:51:05.780
Let's go into the garden,

00:51:05.780 --> 00:51:09.570
there are fruit trees,
you will see, come".

00:51:09.570 --> 00:51:11.370
Thank you.

00:51:11.370 --> 00:51:24.100
